Anonymous Sat 08 May 2021 02:48:09 No.38511385 Report
Quoted By:
>>38509953
I did exactly what you're considering. If you don't have a good ethic, you will burn out quicker without reinforcement.
The upside is that if you do the first draft, let it sit a month, edit it into a second draft, wait a few more weeks, sand off the remaining rough bits and check grammar, then send that third draft out for beta...you will learn to write tighter. Episodic writing has its place, but you have to be halfway decent to make a first draft readable. Mine aren't.

So here's my suggestions.
>lazy
You need to practice writing every day. It needs to be constructive and produce material you keep. A large part of the so called laziness is discarding ideas before you hammer them out on a page. You have to accept that first draft or brainstorming stuff may feel raw or cringy.
>easily distracted
I write in vi. Not gvim. Plain old vi, a window the size of one of my monitors and no window borders. If I need to block out the outside world, I use earplugs or music. But sometimes music is more distraction than good. Once you learn how to be less lazy in your writing habits, you'll have more leeway with things that keep you on task. Me? I can't write and have a movie up on the other monitor. Period.
>work ethic
I track my progress. It's like pushups right after waking up. You make habits. They're unsexy and boring, but productive habits are what take a bad writer to marginal or a good writer to great. They also save you from stress. They make the average, workmanlike days of writing feel less like drudgery.
Work ethic takes time, and putting tools (ideas, characters, phrases) in your back pocket. Don't think about the tool, think through them.
